Problem 1: Content optimisation¶

We currently have a very large library of voices and sounds. Sounds are grouped in Theme packs (Like Xmas, Video Games, movie titles etc). Each week each user gets one pack for free. You are told to maximize the usage of the weekly packs. What would you do? What data would you need?

KPI definition: seconds used per user (per week?)

Objective: max sum(seconds_used) AND min(churn_value)

data:

  • user features (geography, meta-features, etc)
    • churn
  • temporal features
    • woy
    • dow
    • ...
  • theme_id
  • theme features
  • voice/effect_id
  • voice/effect features

Target

sum of seconds the user used a specific unit of aggregation of the product (over a week?)

for each combinations of each user + temporal features, simulate and optimize to determine the best:

  • theme pack
  • composition of the theme pack

by selecting the top 10 with greateast sum of seconds predicted!

problem #1: closed feedback loops

  • introduce an exploration/exploitation mechanism:
    • based on a different level of aggregation?
    • pick randomly 10%?
      • can annoy users with stupid recommendations: instead of completely random, select top 11-20?

Problem 2: Churn reduction¶

Among others, we have a subscription business model where optimizing churn is a key factor. Here you have a telco client churn sample data:

  • a. Gather some insights from the data to identify the factors driving high customer churn.
  • b. Develop a simple churn prediction model to accurately explain customer churn.
  • c. Prescribe personalized actions to retain customers and reduce churn.

In [9]:
cat_cols = []
target_cols = []
num_cols = []
for c in df.columns:
    col_type = df[c].dtype
    if c != "Churn Value":
        if col_type == "object" or col_type.name == "category":
            df[c] = df[c].astype('category')
            cat_cols.append(c)
        elif col_type == "float64" or col_type == "int64":
            df[c] = (df[c] - df[c].min()) / (df[c].max() - df[c].min())
            num_cols.append(c)
    else:
        target_cols.append(c)

# Check where there's missing values
# Plot missing values for the whole dataset 

def missing_values(data):
    df = pd.DataFrame()
    for col in list(data):
        unique_values = data[col].unique()
        try:
            unique_values = np.sort(unique_values)
        except:
            pass
        nans = round(pd.isna(data[col]).sum()/data.shape[0]*100, 1)
        zeros = round((data[col] == 0).sum()/data.shape[0]*100, 1)
        df = df.append(pd.DataFrame([col,
                                     len(unique_values),
                                     nans,
                                     zeros,
                                     #empty
                                    ]).T, ignore_index = True)

    return df.rename(columns = {0: 'Feature',
                                1: 'Unique values',
                                2: 'Nan %',
                                3: 'Zeros %',
                               }).sort_values('Nan %', ascending=False)

Conclusions from EDA¶

Now that we have a better understanding of whats going on in our data, we can already draw a few conclusions:

  • Our target variable is not perfectly balanced. This is important when choosing what algorithm and what evaluation metric we use.
  • Most variables in our dataset are categorical. We will therefore need to encode them to able to feed them to an ML algorithm.
  • There are a few NaNs that we need to impute.
  • Those paying by mailed checked or bank withdraw check are much more likely to churn.
  • It seems that those who have a month-to-month contract are more likely to churn.
  • Customers receiving tech support are less likely to churn.
  • The ones that contracted Fiber are more likely to churn compared to those with DSL.
  • It seems that Monthly Charges play an important role in whether a customer will stay with the company or not. On the one side, customers that churn, pay on average almost $16 more.
  • Under 30are also less likely to churn.
  • The average tenure is lower for churned customers.

The company lost almost 27% of customers last month! Did the Offer help in preventing churn?

We want to compare the churn frequency of customers that received different types of Offer with the churn frequency. Since we have different Offer, the difference-in-means estimator is an unbiased estimator for the average treatment effect (ATE) of the Offer on churn.

$$ ATE = \mathbb{E} \Big[ Y \ \Big| \ W = 1 \Big] - \mathbb{E} \Big[ Y \ \Big| \ W = 0 \Big] $$

We compute the difference-in-means estimate by linear regression. We also include other covariates to improve the efficiency of the estimator.

To do so, we first need to encode the Offerinto different columns - using pd.get_dummies

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

We will pick the best model from our dataframe above and perform a gridsearch with optuna to find the best "settings" (hyperparameters) for the algorithms.

In [59]:
import optuna
from optuna.integration import LightGBMPruningCallback

def objective(trial, X, y):
    param_grid = {
        # "device_type": trial.suggest_categorical("device_type", ['gpu']),
        "n_estimators": trial.suggest_categorical("n_estimators", [10000]),
        "learning_rate": trial.suggest_float("learning_rate", 0.01, 0.3),
        "num_leaves": trial.suggest_int("num_leaves", 20, 3000, step=20),
        "max_depth": trial.suggest_int("max_depth", 3, 12),
        "min_data_in_leaf": trial.suggest_int("min_data_in_leaf", 200, 10000, step=100),
        "lambda_l1": trial.suggest_int("lambda_l1", 0, 100, step=5),
        "lambda_l2": trial.suggest_int("lambda_l2", 0, 100, step=5),
        "min_gain_to_split": trial.suggest_float("min_gain_to_split", 0, 15),
        "bagging_fraction": trial.suggest_float(
            "bagging_fraction", 0.2, 0.95, step=0.1
        ),
        "bagging_freq": trial.suggest_categorical("bagging_freq", [1]),
        "feature_fraction": trial.suggest_float(
            "feature_fraction", 0.2, 0.95, step=0.1
        ),
    }

    cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=3, shuffle=True, random_state=24)

    cv_scores = []
    for idx, (train_idx, test_idx) in enumerate(cv.split(X, y)):
        X_train, X_test = X.iloc[train_idx], X.iloc[test_idx]
        y_train, y_test = y.iloc[train_idx], y.iloc[test_idx]

        model = lgb.LGBMClassifier(objective="binary", **param_grid)
        model.fit(
            X_train,
            y_train,
            eval_set=[(X_test, y_test)],
            eval_metric="binary_logloss",
            early_stopping_rounds=100,
            callbacks=[
                LightGBMPruningCallback(trial, "binary_logloss")
            ],
        )
        
        preds = model.predict_proba(X_test)

        cv_scores.append(log_loss(y_test, preds))

    return np.mean(np.array(cv_scores))

What are the best actions to take based on the model?¶

To evaluate each policy denoted with , we compare its profits with the policy , with its profits without the policy , over every single individual, in a separate validation dataset. Note that this is usually not possible, since, for each customer, we only observe one of the two potential outcomes, with or without the Offer. However, this is synthetic data, so we can do oracle evaluation. If you want to know more about how to evaluate uplift models with real data, I wrote an article about it.

First of all, let's define profits as the net revenue R when the customer does not churn C. $$ \Pi = R (1-C) $$

Therefore, the overall effect on profits for treated individuals is given by the difference between the profits when treated minus the profits when not treated .

$$ \tau_{\pi} = R_1 (1 - C_1) - R_0 (1 - C_0) $$

The effect for untreated individuals is zero.

Policy: Revenue for non-churned customers.

In [62]:
def evaluate_policy(data, policy):
    data['profits'] = (1 - data["Churn Value"]) * data["revenue"]
    baseline = (1-data["Churn Value"]) * data["revenue"]
    effect = policy(data) * (1-data["Churn Value"]) * (data["revenue"]) - (1-policy(data)) * (1-data["Churn Value"]) * data["revenue"]
    return np.sum(effect - baseline)

df["extra_charges"] = df["revenue"] - df["Total Regular Charges"] 
df["total_charges_only"] = (df["revenue"] > df["Total Regular Charges"] ).astype(int)

The policy is not profitable and would lead to an aggregate loss of more than 5442$.

You might think that the problem is the arbitrary threshold, but this is not the case. Below I plot the aggregate effect for all possible policy thresholds.

In [66]:
x = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)
y = [evaluate_policy(df, lambda df : (clf.predict_proba(df[X])[:,1] > k)) for k in x]

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 3))
sns.lineplot(x=x, y=y).set(xlabel='Churn Policy Threshold', title='Aggregate Effect');
ax.axhline(y=0, c='k', lw=3, ls='--');

As we can see, at best we can make zero losses when we don't have any churning customer.

The problem is that the fact that a customer is likely to churn does not imply that the features will have any impact on their churn probability. The two measures are not completely unrelated (e.g. we cannot decrease the churning probability of customers that have 0% probability of churning), but they are not the same thing.

2. Target revenue customers¶

Let's now try a different policy: high-revenue customers. For example, we might change the offer only to the top-10% of customers by revenue. The idea is that, if the policy indeed decreases churn, these are the customers for whom decreasing churn is more profitable.

The policy is again unprofitable, leading to substantial losses. As before, this is not a problem of selecting the threshold as we can see in the plot below. The best we can do is set a threshold so high that we do not treat anyone and we make zero profits.

3. Target churn uplift customers¶

A more sensible approach would be to target customers whose churn probability decreases the most when receiving. We estimate churn uplift using the double-robust estimator, one of the best performing uplift models.
